Analysing trends in Canadian glacers mass

Sergey Sidorov

11/18/2018

Introduction

This is a first example of my tiny-investigation. For more details of data you can find on http://open.canada.ca/en/open-data1.

The data set contains 518 measurments of 6 Canadian glaicer mass balance, collected 1960 till 2007.

Namely, these file includes these glacers:

## [1] "Devon Ice Cap NW - Devon Island, Nunavut"                                             
## [2] "Helm Glacier - southern Coast Mountains (Garibaldi Provincial Park), British Columbia"
## [3] "Meighen Ice Cap - Meighen Island, Nunavut"                                            
## [4] "Peyto Glacier - Rocky Mountain eastern slopes (Banff National Park), Alberta"         
## [5] "Place Glacier - southern Coast Mountains, British Columbia"                           
## [6] "White Glacier - Axel Heiberg Island, Nunavut"

Among six investigated glaciers the most shorly history has Helm Glacier - southern Coast Mountains (Garibaldi Provincial Park), British Columbia.

Meanwhile median value measurments glacier near about zero namely Meighen Ice Cap - Meighen Island, Nunavut.

Just one NA value measurment has Helm Glacier - southern Coast Mountains (Garibaldi Provincial Park), British Columbia.

Hypotesis

We are interested in finding out wheter there is a stat.significant change in mass balance over the observed time period. For these purposes we use R version (3.5.1) and an appropriate stat test called t-test:

t=xmu0s/n.t=xmu0s/n.

The workflow is as follows:

  1. Read the file.
  2. Run t-test for each glacier and collect p-values.
  3. Support the evidence with
    • a table of result;
    • a plot of could help demonstrate results.
